{
  "answer": "**Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1.**\n\nThis text argues that even matters directly perceived require scrutiny due to the unreliability of appearances. Immediately preceding the key verse, it states: \"Untrue things appear true, and true things appear untrue; various states of affairs are seen. Therefore, examination is proper.\" (Nar. M1.62)[^1] The illustrative verse is:\n\n> The sky appears like a surface, a firefly like a fire. But there is no surface in the sky, nor is there fire in a firefly. (Nar. M1.63)[^2]\n\nThis is followed by: \"Therefore, even a matter seen with one's own eyes should be properly examined. By making matters known after examination, one does not deviate from Dharma.\" (Nar. M1.64)[^3]\n\n[^1]: Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-b94fc5).\n[^2]: Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-4363ef).\n[^3]: Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-f1779b).",
